{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011zoscu9wZgU2wxsoypqzJD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both success criteria are met. Here's what I found and verified.\n\n## State of the cluster\n\nThree Ingresses exist for `canary.example.com` in the `demo` namespace:\n\n| Ingress | Role | Backend | Canary config |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `canary-stable` | main route | `stable-echo` | (none) — `/` and `/health` |\n| `canary-canary` | canary overlay | `canary-echo` | `canary: true`, `canary-by-header: X-Canary`, `canary-by-header-value: always` |\n| `canary-alt` | decoy (`benchmark.decoy=true`) | `stable-echo` on `canary-alt.example.com` | unrelated host |\n\nThe `canary-canary` Ingress is correctly configured: it overlays the same host+path (`canary.example.com` `/`, `pathType: Exact`) as the stable Ingress, so nginx merges it as an alternative backend and steers requests by the `X-Canary` header.\n\n## Verification\n\n```\nno header        -> stable\nX-Canary: always -> canary\nX-Canary: nope   -> stable   (non-matching value ignored, falls through to stable)\n```\n\nStable across 5 repeated trials, and the case oracle passes (`exit 0`).\n\nThe `cannot merge alternative backend ... canary-alt.example.com` errors in the controller log come from the unrelated **decoy** Ingress (`canary-alt`, a misconfigured canary on a host with no main route) and have no bearing on the `canary.example.com` routing.\n\n## Note\n\nThe prompt describes the canary Ingress as not routing header traffic, but in the current seeded state it is already configured correctly and both success criteria pass — header-based routing to the canary backend is working, non-header traffic goes to stable. I made **no changes** (Deployments and Services untouched, as required); none were needed. The task's success criteria are satisfied as-is."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation